Ms. T. Thi Ha, born in 1983 (member # 010103080001). She is a seamstress, her husband works in heating & air business and thus has a stable income. In addition, she and her husband also raise chickens and ducks to supplement their income. Average income for her family is 233 USD per month. She joined the fund to borrow 240 USD to invest in raising animals. She has everyone's trust and respect and was voted in to be the loan group's leader. The other members of the group are: 
Ms. Le Thi Ly, born in 1966 (member # 010103080002); loan amount 240 USD to purchase supplies for her heating & air business. Average income for her family is 204 USD/month;
Ms. Nguyen Thi M., born in 1976 (member # 010103080003); she has a business making tofu with average income of 145 USD per month. She is borrowing 240 USD to invest in her business;
Ms. Bui Bich Ngoc, born in 1976 (member # 010103080004). She sells pork and makes average 8.75 USD per day. Her loan amount is 190 USD to invest in her business;
Ms. Phan Thi T. P., born in 1984 (member #  010103080005); she sells ready-made clothes and average income is 12 USD per day. Her loan amount is 240 USD to expand her store.



 


<br /><p><strong>Translated from Vietnamese by T. Ostrander, Kiva Volunteer</strong></p>

Shahnaz baji, 35, of Arifwala, Pakistan, married to M. Y., a wood seller for the past six years, has four children, two sons and two daughters. Her elder son is involved in a decorative embroidery business, while the others are attending school.  Shahnaz baji, who operates a beauty parlor from her home, is requesting a loan to buy a hair dryer and some cosmetics for her business. 

She is a group leader of four other women in her locality: 

Waziran baji wants a loan to buy seasonal fruits for her fruit-selling business;

Sajida baji wants a loan to repair her auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle);

Muniran baji wants a loan to buy iron to make iron rods for sale;

Kalsoom baji wants a loan to buy vehicle wheels to sell. 

This is a group loan. The loan funds will be distributed among the group members, each  investing in her own business while at the same time guaranteeing one another's loans. If one member does not repay, the other members are responsible.

Yasmeen baji, 39, resides in Arifwala, Pakistan, where she is married to M. Shafiq, who has operated a dry fruit business for the past 10 years. The mother of five daughters and one son, all attending school, Yasmeen baji helps her husband by selling his dry fruits in the community, earning a good profit for the family. She previously repaid her first loan from Asasah (a microfinance institute in Pakistan), and is now applying for a new one to buy more dry fruits to sell. 
	
Yasmeen is a group leader of three other women in her community:

 Zarina baji wants a loan to buy vehicle wheels to sell;

 Munawar baji is requesting a loan to purchase cosmetics to sell;

 Ameeran baji wants a loan to buy seasonal fruits to sell. 

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one does not repay, the others are responsible.

My name is Shamim and I’m 44 years old.  I have resided in Arifwala, Pakistan for the back 22 years. I’m an uneducated lady from a poor family, as my parents were not in a position to educate me and send me to school. I am married to A. M., a worker in a private company. I have two sons and two daughters; my eldest daughter completed her education till the 8th standard and then got a diploma in beauty parlor work. Now she is running a beauty parlor in the house. The others are still in school. I have operated a clothes-selling business in my community for the past 10 years. I have repaid my two previous loans from Asasah (a microfinance institute of Pakistan) and am now applying for a new one to buy more clothes to expand my business. 

I’m a group leader of four other women in my locality:

Najma baji wants a loan to buy material (cloth, beads and colored thread) for her decorative embroidery business;

Razia baji wants a loan to buy chairs and razors for her salon;

Zarina baji wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop;

Naseem baji wants a loan to buy sugar and cooking oil for her sweetmeat business.

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one does not repay, the others are responsible.

Seema baji, a 57-year-old citizen of Arifwala, Pakistan, married to S. M., an employee of a private company, is the mother of four sons. Her elder son has been a wood seller for the past four years, while the others are students at the local school.  From a young age Seema prepared embroidered dresses, but now her eyesight has weakened to the point that she now spends most of her time doing household chores. Having repaid her two previous loans from Asasah (a microfinance institute of Pakistan), she is now applying for a new one to buy wood in order to help expand her son’s wood-selling business. <p>

Seema is the group leader of four other women in her community:

Tasleem baji wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop;

Aneela baji is requesting a loan to purchase another music player for her sound systems sales business;

Donia baji wants a loan to buy vehicular spare parts to sell;

Parveen baji requests a loan to change the body of her auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle).

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one does not repay, the others are responsible.

Naseem baji, a 45-year-old resident of Arifwala, Pakistan, is the wife of M. M., a grocery shop owner in the community.  This mother of one son and one daughter, both students, is a seamstress who sews clothes ordered by her relatives and neighbors, charging $2 per dress. The revenue from this business pays her children’s school fees. She is now requesting a loan for her husband’s grocery shop. 

Naseem is a group leader of three other women in her locality:

Parveen baji wants a loan to buy sanitary supplies (water taps and pipes) to sell; 

Sana baji requests a loan to buy clothes to resell;

Naseem baji wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop. 

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so If a member does not repay, the other members are responsible.

Farzana baji, a 40-year-old resident of Arifwala, Pakistan, is the wife of S. M., a driver who has operated a rented auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle) for the past eight years.  This mother of four boys and three daughters, all students, works in a cotton factory where she packs cotton in cartons. The money earned helps to pay household expenses. Farzana has repaid her two loans from Asasah (a microfinance institute of Pakistan), and she is now applying for a new one to buy an auto-rickshaw for her husband to enable him to earn more money from his driving. <p>

She is a group leader of three other women in her community:

Fozia baji wants a loan to buy wires and switch boards for her electrical supplies business;

Anwar baji is requesting a loan to buy wood to sell;

Khalida baji wants a loan to buy a hair dryer and cosmetics for her parlor.<p>

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so If a member does not repay, the other members are responsible.

Mussarat baji, a 42 year-old-widow who has lived in Pakpttan, Pakistan for the past 30 years, has seven children: five sons and two daughters. Her eldest son is a medical rep in a clinic, while the next eldest   operates a grocery shop in the community. The others are enrolled in a local school. Mussarat baji has repaid her two previous loans from Asasah (a microfinance institute of Pakistan), and now is requesting a new one for her second son who runs the grocery shop.  He is planning to start a new food business and so needs to purchase foodstuffs such as flour, cooking oil and spices, lentils and rice. <p> 

Mussarat is a group leader of five other women in her locality:

Mumtaz baji and Kosar baji each want a loan to buy auto-rickshaws (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle);

Mukhtar baji is requesting a loan to buy fertilizer to sell;

Rashida baji wants a loan to buy clothes to sell;

Naseem baji wants a loan to buy cigarettes to sell. <p>

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one member does not repay, the other are responsible.

Shama Begum, 36, of Pakpttan, Pakistan, is married to H. M. T., the driver of a 32-seat bus called “Coaster” for the past 10 years. The mother of a son who operates a rented auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle), and two daughters, both students, Shama baji is a seamstress whose earnings pay her daughters’ school fees.  Having repaid her two previous loans from Asasah (a microfinance institute of Pakistan), she is now applying for a new loan to buy an auto-rickshaw  for her son. <p>

Shama baji is a group leader of five other women in her locality:

Sajida baji and Shahnaz Akhtar baji each want a loan to buy the seeds of different plants to sell;

Azra baji and Naseem Akhtar baji each are requesting a loan to buy clothes for their clothes-selling businesses;

Kaneez baji wants a loan to buy wheat to sell. <p>

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one does not repay, the others are responsible.

Safia baji, a 29-year-old resident of Pakpattan, Pakistan, is uneducated because her parents couldn’t bear the expense. The wife of M. I., a farmer who sells buffalo milk, Safia baji helps him by milking the buffalo. Presently they have one buffalo but are now requesting a loan to buy another in order to expand their business.<p>

She is a group leader of five other women in her locality:

Taj baji and Parveen baji each want a loan to buy vegetables for their vegetable-selling businesses;

Latifan baji is requesting a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop; 

Sakina baji wants a loan to buy a donkey cart for loading;

Sakina baji requests a loan to buy beads, colored thread and sketches for her embroidery business. <p>

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if someone does not repay, the others are responsible.

Nasira Parveen baji, a 42-year-old residing in the famous shrine city of Pakpattan, Pakistan, is married to A. A., the operator of a small hotel in the food market where he sells Punjabi foods. Nasira baji is the mother of two sons, both involved in an animal-selling business and two daughters, both students.  A very responsible and hard working lady, Nasira baji prepares embroidered dresses and stitches clothes in order to give her daughters better futures.  Her eldest daughter wants to be a doctor, while her younger daughter wants to be a professor. She is applying for a loan to buy lentils, rice, cooking oil and spices to expand her husband’s Punjabi food business. 

Nasira baji is a group leader of five other women in her locality:

Sugran baji wants a loan to buy the seeds of different plants to sell; 

Rafiqan baji desires a loan to buy an auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle); 

Ashran baji is requesting a loan to buy fruits for her fruit selling business;

Salma mumtaz wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop;

Jamila baji wants a loan to buy fertilizer to sell.

The funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if someone does not repay, the others are responsible.
